        "id": "3:10",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "6:28",
            "name": "fix the field of rational numbers",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "child",
            "name": "definition of weighted automata",
            "id": "3:114",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "6:30",
                "name": "A weighted automaton is like nondeterministic automaton, except that:",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "3:113",
                "name": "a/1, b/1",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "3:57",
                "name": "The weight of a run is the multiplication of: the initial weight of the first state, the weights of all transitions, the final weight of the last state.",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "3:75",
                "name": "The weight of an input word is the sum of weights of all runs.",
                "disabled": false
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "3:116",
            "name": "Theorem. [Sch\u00fctzenberger 1961] The following problems are in P: (a) equivalence of two weighted automata; (b) zeroness of a single weighted automaton.",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "child",
            "name": "Sch\u00fctzenberger algorithm",
            "id": "4:10",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "4:2",
                "name": "Proof. Consider the zeroness problem of a weighted automaton with n states.",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "6:29",
                "name": "3 is the sum of weights of runs that end in q (using weights for \u03b4 and I, but not for F)",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "4:17",
                "name": "Consider a chain of subspaces V\u2081 \u2286 V\u2082 \u2286 V\u2083 \u2286 ... \u2286 \ud835\udd3dn where Vi is linear combinations of state vectors for input words of length at most i.",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "4:20",
                "name": "Each element of this chain can be computed (represented by a basis), and the chain has length at most n.",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "4:15",
                "name": "The output of the automaton is obtained by applying a linear map f : \ud835\udd3dn \u2192 \ud835\udd3d to the corresponding state vector, and therefore the automaton is zero if and only if all elements of the chain are mapped by f to zero.",
                "disabled": false
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "4:21",
            "name": "Corollary 1. The following problem is in P: given two nondeterministic automata, do they have the same number of runs for every input word?",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "4:22",
            "name": "Corollary 2. The following problem is in P: given two unambiguous automata, do they accept the same words?",
            "disabled": false
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "child",
        "name": "orbit-finite weighted automata",
        "id": "4:25",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "6:31",
            "name": "the atoms \ud835\udd38 are either (\u2115, =) or (\u211a, <)",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "4:29",
            "name": "Definition. A weighted orbit-finite automaton consists of",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "6:32",
            "name": "equivariant orbit-finite sets",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "6:33",
            "name": "equivariant functions",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "6:34",
            "name": "Finitely many states have nonzero initial weight, and for every q \u2208 Q and a \u2208 \u03a3 there are finitely many p \u2208 Q with \u03b4(q, a, p) \u2260 0.",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "5:3",
            "name": "(for nondeterministic automata, this is called \u201cnot guessing atoms\u201d)",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "5:4",
            "name": "The recognized \u201clanguage\u201d is an equivariant function L : \u03a3* \u2192 \ud835\udd3d.",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "show",
            "id": "5:8",
            "name": "Equivalence is decidable",
            "disabled": false
          },
          {
            "type": "child",
            "name": "decidable equivalence",
            "id": "5:10",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "6:36",
                "name": "atom dimension, which is the maximal support size for states (for register automata, this is the number of registers)",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "5:41",
                "name": "Corollary 1. The language equivalence problem for non-guessing unambiguous register automata is in ExpTime and in P for a fixed number of registers.",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "5:43",
                "name": "Previous work [Mottet and Quaas 2016, Clemente and Barloy 2021] had 2ExpSpace and ExpSpace, respectively, and used equality only.",
                "disabled": false
              },
              {
                "type": "show",
                "id": "5:44",
                "name": "Later in this talk: Algorithm works also for guessing automata.",
                "disabled": false
              }
